Swapping is a technique used in memory management to temporarily transfer pages or blocks of data from the main memory to the secondary storage (such as a hard disk) to free up memory space for other processes. This is done when the main memory is not sufficient to hold all the pages of all the processes that are currently running.

When a process needs to access a page that is not currently in the main memory, the operating system swaps out another page from the main memory to the secondary storage, and then swaps in the required page from the secondary storage. This process is known as page replacement.

Swapping is a less efficient method of memory management compared to paging, as the time required to access data from the secondary storage is much slower than that of the main memory. However, it allows more processes to be run concurrently than would be possible with paging alone.
